Understanding R from Excel

c(1,2,3)
## [1] 1 2 3

Vector in Excel 3 rows in 1 column

Type in Excel vs.R

  • Ignores text
  • In R converts to first value
c(1,2,3)
## [1] 1 2 3
myNumbers <- c(1,2,3)
myNumbers * 2.2
## [1] 2.2 4.4 6.6
sum(myNumbers)
## [1] 6
typeof(myNumbers[3])
## [1] "double"
myJunk <- c("1",2,3)
typeof(myNumbers[3])
## [1] "double"
mean(myJunk)
## Warning in mean.default(myJunk): argument is not numeric or logical:
## returning NA
## [1] NA
mean(as.numeric(myJunk))
## [1] 2

Install a package from tab

Vectors in R

Allow quick transformations

sum(myNumbers)
## [1] 6
typeof(myNumbers)
## [1] "double"
mean(myNumbers)
## [1] 2
myDecimals <- c(1.0,2.3,3.4)
sum(myNumbers)
## [1] 6
typeof(myDecimals)
## [1] "double"
myDecimals <- as.numeric(myDecimals)
sum(myDecimals)
## [1] 6.7
typeof(myDecimals)
## [1] "double"
is(myDecimals)
## [1] "numeric" "vector"
is(myNumbers)
## [1] "numeric" "vector"

Can run operations on each item

Vector operations like multiply

myNumbers * 2.2
## [1] 2.2 4.4 6.6

Different from aggregates like sum Summarize into single value (vector of 1)

sum(myNumbers)
## [1] 6

na =NULL

badBoyz <- c("A",1,32)
is.numeric(badBoyz)
## [1] FALSE
as.numeric(badBoyz)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
## [1] NA  1 32
sum(as.numeric(badBoyz), na.rm = TRUE)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
## [1] 33

Matrix

Install a package from tab

myMatrix <- c(c(2,3,4),c(6,3,5))
myMatrix
## [1] 2 3 4 6 3 5
myMatrix <- matrix(myMatrix, nrow = 3, ncol = 2)
myMatrix
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    2    6
## [2,]    3    3
## [3,]    4    5

  • Excel is Column-Row (B2)

  • R is row-column[3,2] #Mo Matrix
  • Can get rows or columns

  • Result is vector

sum(myMatrix)
## [1] 23
myMatrix[,1]
## [1] 2 3 4
myMatrix * 4
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    8   24
## [2,]   12   12
## [3,]   16   20
myMatrix[1,]
## [1] 2 6

Tables in Excel =DataFrame in R

#DataFrame$ColumnName

data.frame(myMatrix)
colnames(myMatrix) <- c("First Column","Second Column")
myMatrix
##      First Column Second Column
## [1,]            2             6
## [2,]            3             3
## [3,]            4             5
myMatrix <- data.frame(myMatrix)
typeof(myMatrix$First.Column)
## [1] "double"

Data Provenance

  • Excel is destructive
  • Make changes =changes data
  • R can keep original data
  • If make mistakes can rerun the script

Filter in View mode

Functions vs Sub

  • Functions return a value
  • In R have return statement in parens
first_function <- function(x){return (x)}
first_function("x")
## [1] "x"
  • Can be on multiple lines
snoopdogit <-
  function(x){
    return (paste(x,"izzle",sep=""))
    }
snoopdogit("sing")
## [1] "singizzle"

Make your own functions

fixemplid <- function(x){
  
  if (nchar(x)=="6"){
    return (paste("00",x, sep=""))
  }
   

}
fixemplid(("123456"))
## [1] "00123456"

Pro advice

  • Do 1 thing
  • Verify it works (Check it in)
  • Do the next thing #Make it better
fixemplid <- function(x){
  
  if (nchar(x)=="6"){
    return (paste("00",x, sep=""))
  }
  if (nchar(x)=="7"){
    return (paste("0",x, sep=""))
  }
  return (x)

}
fixemplid(("123456"))
## [1] "00123456"
three_emplids <- c("123456","1234567","12345678")
lapply(three_emplids, fixemplid)
## [[1]]
## [1] "00123456"
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "01234567"
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] "12345678"
